A new science
In this summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers met to think about the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of sciences have been answered.
Considering the great challenges, one is of the opinion that there is little more to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Secondly, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solution is to be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, many people believe that the only difficult part of the work would be to use new technologies to benefit humanity by utilizing already known natural laws.
Who could deny that?
Today's models do function, after all.
A growing group of scientists, however, points out phenomena that cannot be explained well with the current theories.
Although these problems occur more frequently, they are also skillfully avoided because the science to explain these problems simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the origin of entire systems.
In the individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is relatively well secured.
The physics, at least the part with which we normal folk are confronted, is well researched.
The chemistry and biochemistry are also standing on solid foundations – there are indeed still a few things in our body that we don't understand, but it can be assumed that the fundamental mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
There are also the new social sciences that deal with humans and societies.
In every one of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are solidified and are largely beyond controversy.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases, a scientist is an expert in more than one field area, because these worlds and languages are so different.
This means that we cannot find an answer to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
Think, for example, of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction occurs on the basis of physics. The information mediated by this process is transmitted due to the laws of electricity.
There is also a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and transmit information in this way.
When interacting between two brains, a new level is added: Here, information exchange occurs through language, signs, and conceptions.
At each level, it's about exchanging information, and there are suitable theories that explain the processes on individual levels.
However, information is also exchanged between individual levels, but there is no science that could even approximately explain the information exchange between these levels.
To compensate for this lack, some scientists have tried to redefine the instrumentation for explaining processes within a level so that it can then be applied to another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" on a cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanation patterns works quite well, but the underlying problem is not solved in this way: How is the information exchanged between individual levels composed and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this shameful lack of knowledge about how the overall system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary researchers who came together in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and fields of study and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discussion.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy", where the scientific foundations of a level are adapted and supplemented and transferred to another level.
Others, on the other hand, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
According to their view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge from scientists who currently do not have access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities that take place under the sign of "science" have, similar to their counterparts from the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
One believes that developing countries should build similar resources as industrial countries. However, this could stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these - sometimes revolutionary - ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not associated with the major institutions.
The most thoughtful approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a shortage of computer capacity at every corner and end.
The most genius and in the truest sense of the word most world-shattering insights in the field of physics in the last decades did not come as expected from the known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that helped cognitive scientists to important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of the second generation of artificial intelligence (so-called "autonomous agents") come today from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements went down in history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified for which explanations need to be found.
Further experts from innovative regions will be added to this group in order to identify the problems that could be solved if this new science is developed in the future, or discovered, as you will.

